In the latitude of Rhodes the same three signs were supposed to rise with 116Ο of the equator3 and Berosus allowed man an extreme term of 116 years of life. An Italian, thanks to the inclination of the pole, might hope to live longer than any Rhodian or Egyptian. The. degrees of the equator, χρόνοι ἰσημερινοί, since each of them accorded one year of life, were themselves called ἔτη; and by dividing their number into the number of the eorre- sponding zodiacal degrees it was possible to ascertain how many months and days corresponded to each of these latter.
